sec.p:
Assume that there is a semantics-based ordering relation ≤ defined on X. So, X can be considered formally as an abstract algebra AX = (X, G, C, H, ≤), where G = {c−, c+}, C = {0, W, 1}, H = H+ ∪ H− is the set of unary operations (H+ is the set of all positive hedges and H− is the set of all negative ones), X\C = H(G) is the set generated from G - and ≤ is a partially ordering relation on X. We have:


h > x if kx < x, for all h ∈ H+, k ∈ H−;

if h < k then (hx > x ⇒ kx > x) and (x > hx ⇒ hx > kx);

if ∃x (x < hx < khx or x > hx > khx) then {(y < hy ⇒ y < hy < ky) and (hy < y ⇒ khy < hy < y)} for all y;

if ∃x (x < khx < hx or x > khx > hx) then {(y < hy ⇒ y < khy < hy) and (hy < y ⇒ hy < khy < y)} for all y.

An fm: X → [0, 1] is said to be a fuzziness measure of terms in X if:


(fm1) fm(c−) + fm(c+) = 1 and ∑h∈Hfm(hu)=fm(u), ∀u ∈ X; in this case fm is called complete;

(fm2) for the constants 0, W and 1, fm(0) = fm(W) = fm(1) = 0;

(fm3) ∀x, y ∈ X, ∀h ∈ H, fm(hx)fm(x)=fm(hy)fm(y), that is, this proportion does not depend on specific elements and, hence, it is called the fuzziness measure of the hedge h and denoted by µ(h).

We assume that H− = {h–1,…,h–q}, where h–1 < h–2 <…< h–q, H+ = {h1,…, hp}, where h1<…<hp. For each fuzziness measure fm on X the following statements hold:


fm(hx) = µ(h)fm(x), for every x ∈ X;

fm(c−) + fm(c+) = 1;

∑-q≤i≤p,i≠0fm(hic)=fm(c), c ∈{c−, c+};

∑-q≤i≤p,i≠0fm(hix)=fm(x);

∑-q≤i≤-1μ(hi)=α and ∑1≤i≤pμ(hi)=β, where α, β > 0 and α + β = 1.

A mapping φ: 𝒳 → [0, 1] is said to be a SQM of 𝒜𝒳, provided that the following conditions hold:


φ is a one-to-one mapping from X into [0,1] and preserves the order on X, that is, for all x, y ∈ X, x < y ⇒ φ(x) < φ(y) and φ(0) = 0, φ(1) = 1, where 0, 1 ∈ C;

continuity: ∀x ∈ X, φ(Φx) = infimum φ(H(x)) and φ(Σx) = supremum φ(H(x)).

In the algebraic approach, it is interesting that we can define the sign of terms in every term-domain, that is Sign(x) ∈ {−1, 0, 1}, for all x ∈ X. A function Sign: X → {−1, 0, 1} is a mapping that is defined recursively as follows, for h, h'∈ H and c ∈ {c−, c+}:


Sign(c−) = − 1, Sign(c+) = +1;

Sign(hc) = − Sign(c), if h is negative with regard to c;

Sign(hc) = + Sign(c), if h is positive with regard to c;

Sign(h'hx) = − Sign(hx), if h’hx ≠ hx and h' is negative with regard to h;

Sign(h'hx) = + Sign(hx), if h’hx ≠ hx and h' is positive with regard to h;

Sign(h'hx) = 0 if h’hx = hx.

There exists a natural and close connection between a fuzziness measure and a SQM. To deal with this, we define a mapping from X into [0, 1] associated with a given fuzziness measure fm: Let fm be a fuzziness measure on X. A mapping φ: X → [0, 1], which is induced by fm on X, is defined as follows (x = hm … h2h1c+/):


ν(W) = θ = fm(c−), ν(c−) = θ − αfm(c−) = βfm(c−), φ(c+) = θ + αfm(c+);

fm(x) = fm(hm … h2h1c+/−)  = µ(hm) … µ(h2)µ(h1)fm(c+/−);

if j ≤ p then
ν(hjx)=ν(x)+Sign(hjx)[∑i≠jpfm(hjx)   -0.5(1-Sign(hjx)Sign(hihjx)(β-α))fm(hjx)];


if j > p then
ν(hjx)=ν(x)+Sign(hjx)[∑i≠p+1jfm(hjx)   -0.5(1-Sign(hjx)Sign(hihjx)(β-α))fm(hjx)].

(1) Determine the control problem. Suppose that we have a fuzzy control problem of an application for which we can determine the following factors:


- a Fuzzy Associative Memory (FAM) table with linguistic descriptions, which represents an expert knowledge of the application domain for defining the state and control action values of the controlled object in every control cycle;

- establish a discrete control model, denoted by CM, which defines the computation relationship between numeric-valued states of the controlled object and numeric-valued control actions in each control cycle;

- a criterion for evaluating the effectiveness of the control method: goal function g(x1, … , xm), where x1, x2, … , xm and u can be computed by formulas defined by the established CM.

(2) Construct an optimal control algorithm based on SQMs. This step consists of the following tasks:

- considering SQMs of the linguistic variables of the states of the controlled object and the control action as design variables and determining their intervals;

- constructing a fitness algorithm to evaluate the fitness level of the parameters for the GA based on the calculation of the state values of the controlled object and the control action.

- optimizing the parameters using the GA.
